WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:02.973
An AI Agent says it completed the task.

2
00:00:02.923 --> 00:00:07.152
The report looks polished, the final message sounds confident, and every

3
00:00:07.152 --> 00:00:08.855
checklist item appears green.

4
00:00:08.855 --> 00:00:12.719
But the file may be in the wrong folder, the refund may not exist in the

5
00:00:12.719 --> 00:00:16.529
database, or the research answer may contain claims that its sources do

6
00:00:16.529 --> 00:00:17.173
not support.

7
00:00:17.173 --> 00:00:20.942
That gap is the central problem of AI Agent evaluation.

8
00:00:20.942 --> 00:00:23.500
A completion message is only a claim.

9
00:00:23.500 --> 00:00:27.118
Reliable acceptance asks whether the intended state actually exists,

10
00:00:27.118 --> 00:00:30.684
whether the work met clear quality boundaries, and whether the same

11
00:00:30.684 --> 00:00:33.557
Agent can succeed again instead of getting lucky once.

12
00:00:33.557 --> 00:00:37.605
Anthropic's guidance on Agent evals makes one point especially useful:

13
00:00:37.605 --> 00:00:41.537
the flexibility that makes Agents valuable also makes them harder to

14
00:00:41.537 --> 00:00:41.826
test.

15
00:00:41.826 --> 00:00:46.010
They act over many turns, call tools, change environments, and sometimes

16
00:00:46.010 --> 00:00:49.788
reach a good result through a path the evaluator did not predict.

17
00:00:49.788 --> 00:00:53.211
So this video will build a practical acceptance method.

18
00:00:53.211 --> 00:00:57.174
You will learn how to define a fair task, separate the transcript from

19
00:00:57.174 --> 00:01:01.023
the outcome, select code, model, and human graders, measure repeated

20
00:01:01.023 --> 00:01:04.759
trials, and check whether the evaluation itself is misleading you.

21
00:01:04.759 --> 00:01:08.750
At the end, you will have an AI Agent Acceptance Sheet that turns “it

22
00:01:08.750 --> 00:01:12.856
feels done” into evidence you can review, repeat, and use for a release

23
00:01:12.856 --> 00:01:13.377
decision.

24
00:01:13.516 --> 00:01:17.071
Start with the smallest unit of evaluation: a task.

25
00:01:17.021 --> 00:01:21.242
A task gives the AI Agent defined inputs and success criteria.

26
00:01:21.242 --> 00:01:25.411
One attempt at that task is a trial, and a collection of related tasks

27
00:01:25.411 --> 00:01:27.079
becomes an evaluation suite.

28
00:01:27.079 --> 00:01:31.060
The distinction matters because a vague request produces a vague score.

29
00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:34.809
If two domain experts cannot independently decide whether the task

30
00:01:34.809 --> 00:01:37.877
passed, the specification is not yet ready to measure.

31
00:01:37.877 --> 00:01:41.517
The Agent should know what it must produce, where the result belongs,

32
00:01:41.517 --> 00:01:43.416
and which constraints are essential.

33
00:01:43.416 --> 00:01:46.627
Next, separate the transcript from the outcome.

34
00:01:46.627 --> 00:01:51.033
The transcript records messages, tool calls, intermediate results,

35
00:01:51.033 --> 00:01:52.502
reasoning, and errors.

36
00:01:52.502 --> 00:01:56.406
The outcome is the final state left in the environment after the trial.

37
00:01:56.406 --> 00:02:00.589
For a booking Agent, “your flight is booked” appears in the transcript.

38
00:02:00.589 --> 00:02:03.800
The outcome is a valid reservation in the database.

39
00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:08.020
For a coding Agent, a convincing explanation is not the outcome; the

40
00:02:08.020 --> 00:02:11.867
changed repository, passing tests, and preserved behavior are.

41
00:02:11.867 --> 00:02:14.925
A grader scores one dimension of performance.

42
00:02:14.925 --> 00:02:19.053
It may check an exact state, apply a quality rubric, or ask a human

43
00:02:19.053 --> 00:02:21.271
expert to judge a subjective result.

44
00:02:21.271 --> 00:02:24.635
A task can use several graders because success is often

45
00:02:24.635 --> 00:02:25.675
multidimensional.

46
00:02:25.675 --> 00:02:28.666
Finally, remember what you are evaluating.

47
00:02:28.666 --> 00:02:31.310
An AI Agent is not only a model.

48
00:02:31.310 --> 00:02:35.858
The harness supplies instructions, tools, state, and orchestration.

49
00:02:35.858 --> 00:02:39.755
A weak tool contract or unstable environment can make the same model

50
00:02:39.755 --> 00:02:43.079
fail, so the model and harness must be evaluated together.

51
00:02:43.079 --> 00:02:47.656
First, define one task with explicit inputs and success criteria.

52
00:02:47.656 --> 00:02:51.262
Second, separate the transcript from the final outcome.

53
00:02:51.262 --> 00:02:54.954
Third, evaluate the model and the Agent harness together.

54
00:02:55.084 --> 00:02:59.266
The first acceptance question is simple: did the intended final state

55
00:02:59.266 --> 00:02:59.630
exist?

56
00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:03.116
Outcome checks are usually stronger than trusting the Agent's own

57
00:03:03.116 --> 00:03:06.542
completion message because they inspect the artifact, database,

58
00:03:06.542 --> 00:03:09.099
application state, or external effect directly.

59
00:03:09.099 --> 00:03:13.933
For structured work, code-based graders are fast, cheap, reproducible,

60
00:03:13.933 --> 00:03:15.176
and easy to debug.

61
00:03:15.176 --> 00:03:19.611
Unit tests, schema checks, static analysis, exact matches, and state

62
00:03:19.611 --> 00:03:23.589
assertions can verify conditions that have objective answers.

63
00:03:23.589 --> 00:03:26.253
But deterministic graders can be brittle.

64
00:03:26.253 --> 00:03:30.173
A valid answer may use different wording, a different file structure, or

65
00:03:30.173 --> 00:03:33.821
a creative solution that satisfies the user while missing an overly

66
00:03:33.821 --> 00:03:35.128
narrow expected pattern.

67
00:03:35.128 --> 00:03:39.058
Passing the evaluator should require solving the task, not guessing the

68
00:03:39.058 --> 00:03:41.051
evaluator's favorite implementation.

69
00:03:41.051 --> 00:03:44.089
Model-based graders help with open-ended work.

70
00:03:44.089 --> 00:03:48.046
A clear rubric can score groundedness, completeness, instruction

71
00:03:48.046 --> 00:03:50.272
following, or communication quality.

72
00:03:50.272 --> 00:03:53.761
Pairwise comparison and separate dimension scores are often more

73
00:03:53.761 --> 00:03:57.032
reliable than one vague request to judge everything at once.

74
00:03:57.032 --> 00:04:01.167
Model graders are still nondeterministic and must be calibrated against

75
00:04:01.167 --> 00:04:02.041
human judgment.

76
00:04:02.041 --> 00:04:06.145
Give them structured criteria and an “unknown” option when evidence is

77
00:04:06.145 --> 00:04:06.907
insufficient.

78
00:04:06.907 --> 00:04:10.796
For high-stakes or specialized work, human experts remain the reference

79
00:04:10.796 --> 00:04:14.137
used to check whether automated grading matches real quality.

80
00:04:14.137 --> 00:04:18.267
The practical pattern is outcome first, then behavior where behavior

81
00:04:18.267 --> 00:04:18.753
matters.

82
00:04:18.753 --> 00:04:22.814
Verify the final state, add transcript checks for safety or efficiency,

83
00:04:22.814 --> 00:04:26.875
and avoid requiring one exact sequence of tool calls when several valid

84
00:04:26.875 --> 00:04:28.762
paths can reach the right result.

85
00:04:28.762 --> 00:04:32.907
First, verify the final state before trusting the Agent's claim.

86
00:04:32.907 --> 00:04:37.464
Second, combine deterministic, model-based, and human graders by

87
00:04:37.464 --> 00:04:38.176
dimension.

88
00:04:38.176 --> 00:04:42.493
Third, grade essential outcomes without overfitting to one valid path.

89
00:04:42.628 --> 00:04:46.904
One successful trial does not prove that an AI Agent is reliable.

90
00:04:46.854 --> 00:04:50.770
Agent behavior varies between runs, so a pass can reflect a stable

91
00:04:50.770 --> 00:04:55.043
capability, a lucky trajectory, or an evaluator that missed the failure.

92
00:04:55.043 --> 00:04:58.528
This is why each important task should run more than once.

93
00:04:58.528 --> 00:05:02.490
The distribution of results reveals whether the Agent usually succeeds,

94
00:05:02.490 --> 00:05:06.508
occasionally succeeds, or fails in a consistent way that one trial would

95
00:05:06.508 --> 00:05:06.787
hide.

96
00:05:06.787 --> 00:05:10.710
Pass at k asks whether at least one of k attempts succeeds.

97
00:05:10.710 --> 00:05:14.712
It is useful when exploration matters and one working solution is

98
00:05:14.712 --> 00:05:15.143
enough.

99
00:05:15.143 --> 00:05:19.105
Pass to the k asks whether all k attempts succeed, which is the harder

100
00:05:19.105 --> 00:05:22.898
and more relevant bar when users expect the same task to work every

101
00:05:22.898 --> 00:05:23.181
time.

102
00:05:23.181 --> 00:05:25.278
The difference is operational.

103
00:05:25.278 --> 00:05:29.507
A research assistant that proposes several hypotheses may benefit from

104
00:05:29.507 --> 00:05:30.595
one strong result.

105
00:05:30.595 --> 00:05:34.243
A customer-facing Agent that processes refunds needs consistent

106
00:05:34.243 --> 00:05:38.238
correctness, because one failure can create a real financial or trust

107
00:05:38.238 --> 00:05:38.701
problem.

108
00:05:38.701 --> 00:05:41.903
Reliability also depends on task balance.

109
00:05:41.903 --> 00:05:45.893
Test cases where a behavior should happen and cases where it should not.

110
00:05:45.893 --> 00:05:49.701
If you only reward searching, the Agent may search everything.

111
00:05:49.701 --> 00:05:53.691
If you only reward refusal, it may stop doing useful work.

112
00:05:53.691 --> 00:05:55.681
Keep trials isolated.

113
00:05:55.681 --> 00:05:59.640
Shared files, cached state, resource exhaustion, or history from a

114
00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:03.478
previous run can either inflate performance or create correlated

115
00:06:03.478 --> 00:06:04.018
failures.

116
00:06:04.018 --> 00:06:07.384
The test environment should resemble production while resetting the

117
00:06:07.384 --> 00:06:09.393
state that would contaminate comparison.

118
00:06:09.393 --> 00:06:13.220
First, run multiple trials because one pass can be luck.

119
00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:17.203
Second, choose pass at k for discovery and pass to the k for

120
00:06:17.203 --> 00:06:17.999
consistency.

121
00:06:17.999 --> 00:06:22.143
Third, balance tasks and isolate the environment before comparing

122
00:06:22.143 --> 00:06:22.653
results.

123
00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:26.355
A low score does not always mean the AI Agent is weak.

124
00:06:26.305 --> 00:06:30.605
The task may be ambiguous, the environment may be broken, or the grader

125
00:06:30.605 --> 00:06:32.180
may reject a valid answer.

126
00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:35.064
Evaluation quality must be tested too.

127
00:06:35.064 --> 00:06:37.564
Start with failures you already see.

128
00:06:37.564 --> 00:06:41.487
Manual checks, support tickets, production bugs, and difficult edge

129
00:06:41.487 --> 00:06:45.703
cases are high-value seeds because they represent real user expectations

130
00:06:45.703 --> 00:06:48.045
rather than imaginary benchmark puzzles.

131
00:06:48.045 --> 00:06:52.362
Write each task so two qualified reviewers can reach the same verdict.

132
00:06:52.362 --> 00:06:56.201
Include the input, required outcome, important constraints, and

133
00:06:56.201 --> 00:06:58.333
everything the grader will inspect.

134
00:06:58.333 --> 00:07:01.905
Then create a reference solution that proves the task is solvable and

135
00:07:01.905 --> 00:07:04.545
that the graders can recognize a known good result.

136
00:07:04.545 --> 00:07:07.151
Build balanced sets and begin small.

137
00:07:07.151 --> 00:07:11.486
A useful early suite can contain a few dozen realistic tasks instead of

138
00:07:11.486 --> 00:07:13.074
hundreds of weak examples.

139
00:07:13.074 --> 00:07:17.041
As the product matures, add harder cases that distinguish improvements

140
00:07:17.041 --> 00:07:20.612
and convert solved capability tests into regression protection.

141
00:07:20.612 --> 00:07:23.756
Read transcripts and grades from many trials.

142
00:07:23.756 --> 00:07:27.112
A failed trace tells you whether the Agent made a genuine mistake,

143
00:07:27.112 --> 00:07:30.672
whether the harness blocked progress, or whether the grader punished a

144
00:07:30.672 --> 00:07:31.689
reasonable solution.

145
00:07:31.689 --> 00:07:36.065
If failures do not look fair, revise the evaluation before optimizing

146
00:07:36.065 --> 00:07:36.699
the Agent.

147
00:07:36.699 --> 00:07:39.208
Treat the suite as a living artifact.

148
00:07:39.208 --> 00:07:43.182
Models improve, products change, user behavior shifts, and

149
00:07:43.182 --> 00:07:45.237
once-difficult tasks saturate.

150
00:07:45.237 --> 00:07:49.261
Ownership, regular maintenance, production monitoring, and periodic

151
00:07:49.261 --> 00:07:52.324
human calibration keep the signal useful over time.

152
00:07:52.324 --> 00:07:56.580
First, turn real failures into unambiguous tasks with reference

153
00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:57.256
solutions.

154
00:07:57.256 --> 00:08:01.555
Second, read transcripts to tell Agent errors from grader errors.

155
00:08:01.555 --> 00:08:06.084
Third, keep the suite current as capabilities, products, and risks

156
00:08:06.084 --> 00:08:06.564
change.

157
00:08:06.700 --> 00:08:10.323
Now turn the method into one AI Agent Acceptance Sheet.

158
00:08:10.273 --> 00:08:14.298
Use it for a single high-value task before a release, for a repeated

159
00:08:14.298 --> 00:08:17.494
workflow, or as the seed of a larger evaluation suite.

160
00:08:17.494 --> 00:08:19.340
Block one is Outcome.

161
00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:23.551
Name the user-visible result, the final state that proves it exists, the

162
00:08:23.551 --> 00:08:26.359
acceptance threshold, and the evidence location.

163
00:08:26.359 --> 00:08:29.446
Do not use “Agent said done” as evidence.

164
00:08:29.446 --> 00:08:31.600
Block two is Task Setup.

165
00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:35.738
Record the input, tools, permissions, starting state, important

166
00:08:35.738 --> 00:08:38.234
constraints, and a reference solution.

167
00:08:38.234 --> 00:08:42.209
This makes the task reproducible and exposes whether the environment

168
00:08:42.209 --> 00:08:43.436
itself creates noise.

169
00:08:43.436 --> 00:08:45.667
Block three is Grader Mix.

170
00:08:45.667 --> 00:08:49.567
Choose deterministic checks for objective state, model rubrics for

171
00:08:49.567 --> 00:08:53.821
open-ended quality, and human review for calibration or expert judgment.

172
00:08:53.821 --> 00:08:58.272
Give each grader one clear dimension instead of one grader an undefined

173
00:08:58.272 --> 00:08:58.523
job.

174
00:08:58.523 --> 00:09:00.686
Block four is Reliability.

175
00:09:00.686 --> 00:09:04.769
Set the number of trials, the metric that matches the product need, and

176
00:09:04.769 --> 00:09:06.494
the minimum acceptable result.

177
00:09:06.494 --> 00:09:10.808
One success may be enough for exploration, but repeated customer actions

178
00:09:10.808 --> 00:09:12.186
need a consistency bar.

179
00:09:12.186 --> 00:09:14.975
Block five is Eval Health and Decision.

180
00:09:14.975 --> 00:09:19.243
Record transcript spot checks, known grader gaps, environment failures,

181
00:09:19.243 --> 00:09:23.210
exceptions, the release decision, and the next failure that should

182
00:09:23.210 --> 00:09:24.292
become a new task.

183
00:09:24.292 --> 00:09:28.128
The sheet evaluates both the Agent and your confidence in the test.

184
00:09:28.128 --> 00:09:32.148
First, write the outcome and task setup before choosing a grader.

185
00:09:32.148 --> 00:09:37.053
Second, collect final-state evidence, behavior evidence, and repeated

186
00:09:37.053 --> 00:09:37.551
trials.

187
00:09:37.551 --> 00:09:42.282
Third, record the release decision, exceptions, and next test to add.

188
00:09:42.412 --> 00:09:46.063
An AI Agent's polished completion message is not proof.

189
00:09:46.013 --> 00:09:50.129
Reliable acceptance turns the intended result into a task, inspects the

190
00:09:50.129 --> 00:09:54.071
final state, and asks whether success repeats under fair conditions.

191
00:09:54.071 --> 00:09:57.879
First, define success before the AI Agent starts.

192
00:09:57.879 --> 00:10:01.590
Second, verify final state with the right grader mix.

193
00:10:01.590 --> 00:10:05.360
Third, repeat trials and audit the evaluation itself.

194
00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:09.583
Use the AI Agent Acceptance Sheet to record the outcome, setup,

195
00:10:09.583 --> 00:10:14.074
evidence, grader mix, reliability bar, evaluation gaps, and release

196
00:10:14.074 --> 00:10:14.677
decision.

197
00:10:14.677 --> 00:10:17.956
That is how “done” becomes a result you can trust.

198
00:10:17.956 --> 00:10:19.802
Follow Tiny Agent.

199
00:10:19.802 --> 00:10:22.225
Tiny Agent helps you get better at using AI.
